item.title: Small Airtag Collar Strap
item.description:
This is a slim air tag collar that I designed for my cat's breakaway collar (12mm width), but it may work for a small dog collar as well. I didn't want the airtag to dangle in the front. It sits flush to the collar with the bottom of the tag against the collar.

Must be printed in a flexible filament, I used TPU. Keep the infill as low as possible for more flex on the strap. I printed it at 5% infill with the rounded side down and supports on the build plate.

item.title: DIN rail mount for wago clone lever terminal blocks
item.description:
Metric DIN rail mount for cloned wago-style "lever" terminal blocks that are commonly sold on Amazon AliBaba, etc...

There are clones of the WAGO lever action terminal blocks on AliBaba, Amazon, and other stores that have a different mounting system. In order to mount these on a DIN rail, you will need this “push to lock” style mount.

Print at .2 to .3 layer height with 2 perimeters, 100% infill. Best materials to use are ASA, ABS, or PETG.

Two small supports are already built into the model for the tab that goes into the terminal block. Remove them!

item.title: soda bottle combination lock
item.description:
This is a combination lock for soda bottles. For a long time a have been wanting to design an make a lock for soda bottles, and my inspiration for that - my family members often would drink my soda without permision. The last straw that finaly pushed me to design this was when my sibling drank half of my soda and added water to it so it doesn't look like someone had emptied half of the bootle... the diluted "soda" of course wasn't drinkable, plain tap water had a better taste.

Once I designed it I realized that it could also be used as a child safety lock for those people who like to store liquids that aren't digestible such as oil, petrol, solvents, and other.

fusion 360 file included
STEP files included

this is a version 3 of the combination lock, ...so...what happened to version 1 and 2?
version 1 - couldn't asseble due to improper tolerances.
version 2 - assembled with glue, so... once its glued the combination couldn't be changed
version 3 - slightly stronger geometry and insted of glue it uses 3x M3 bolts and nuts (10mm long bolts), the combination can be changed by changing the combination rings.

known issues with version 3:
very loose tolerances,
quite easy to decode,
bulky,
rings lack fixation - rotates too freely therefore can be challenging to align the rings to unlock

version 4 - work in progress, main objectives: make the lock smaller and make it a lot harder to decode, in other words, a complete redesign required.

for assembly 3x M3 10mm long bolts and 3x M3 nuts required

item.title: Game Controller Hanger
item.description:
Game Controller Hanger

Description

This is a hanger to hold a game controller under a table.

  • The hanger features a two leg claw design, to hold on to the game controller.
  • The wide radius and the angle of the hanger enable an easy setting and removing of the controller, even when not looking (which would be difficult, when mounted under the table).
  • The sides are rounded, so the controller self centers on the hanger when placed or when slightly nudged or shaken.
  • The oval hole on the back enables the controller to be plugged in and charged.

Compatibility

Any controller with a flat section of at least 65 mm between the two handles should be compatible with this hanger.

The following Controller had been tested and are compatible with this hanger:

  • Xbox Series X Controller
  • Xbox One Controller
  • Nintendo Switch Pro Controller

If you test this hanger with other controllers, please give feedback in the comments to let other users know if this controller is compatible.

Assembly

The hanger is printed in one piece.
You can use Ø3 mm - 3.5 mm screws (recommended) or double-sided tape to secure the hanger to your table.
(The screw holes are Ø4 mm. So you may be able to use Ø4 mm screws as well.)

item.title: Emboss tile template generator
item.description:
OpenSCAD file for creating tile for the Emboss paper stamp (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4973257) I am sure others can clean this up and make it more streamlined, but it worked for what I needed it to do. I did not mark this as a "Customizer" as I honestly am not sure how to enable using a local image file for that.

Tried to add a slight tilt to the tiles to get them to sit together a bit more flush.

Currently setup to look for a *.png file in a "tiles" directory. PNG file should be simple black and white outline / silhouette of design.

Added example image file and resulting tiles in case that is helpful.

Hopefully this helps out others wanting to create their own tiles!
